                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_Douce_108-item1">
                     <author key="person_10428840">John Mirk</author>
                     <title key="work_2743">Festial</title>
                     <note>Containing forty-four sermons and prologue</note>
                     <note>The signatures show breaks after fols 174, 190, 204, 282, but the book does not seem to be imperfect</note>
                     <note>Incomplete</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="enm">Middle English</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                  
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>paper</support><extent>iv + <measure type="leaf" quantity="358">358</measure> pages. Contains two initial fly-leaves plus
                           354 numbered pages, pp. 351-354 being the end fly-leaves. The pages really amount to 358, since pages 203 and 281 are triplicated 
                           (Wakelin, 'The manuscripts of John Mirk's Festial' (1967) p. 105)
                           <dimensions type="binding" unit="in"><height>8.75</height><width>6.125</width></dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <condition>Fol. 1 is injured. There is a hole burned in pages 2-3 and a 15th-century hand has rewritten the singed words at the edges (Daniel Wakelin, 
                           <title><ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/434020/bodleian_library_western_medieval_manuscripts_bibliography/tags/MS.%20Douce%20108/search/Designing%20English%3A%20Early%20Literature%20on%20the%20Page/titleCreatorYear/items/HBQKUUHG/item-list">Designing English</ref></title> (Bodleian, 2018), p. 131 and fn. 343</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  
                  <handDesc><handNote>
                     In the same hand as <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_4730">MS. Douce 60</ref>, the version of Mirk's <title>Instructions</title> 
                     which is contained in <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_4482">MS. Douce 103</ref> (Wakelin, 'The manuscripts of John Mirk's Festial', p. 105), 
                  </handNote></handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>There is some rubrication, and some of the titles and the initial letters of some homilies are in red, 
                        but rubrication is used very sparingly between pages 65 and 112, 175 and 203, and after 270 (Wakelin, 'The manuscripts of John Mirk's Festial' (1967), p. 105)
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>Latin interpolations occur on pages 205 and 282. Francis Douce supplied an index of the contents</additions>
